Envelope control variant (analog gain):
MCU PWM (envelope) ──► Low-pass filter (RC) ──► Op-amp non-inverting input
                                           └─► Op-amp output ──► MOSFET gate (instead of direct PWM)
How It Maps Your Grammar
Layer l → Base PWM frequency band: e.g., l=0 (planetary) → ~40 kHz, l=1 → ~100 kHz, l=2–4 → 150–250 kHz (scale metallic(k) × center_freq / k)
Branch n → PWM duty cycle or harmonic multiplier: n even = 50% duty (stable build), n odd = inverted/pulsed (prune flavor). Use tone() or analogWriteFrequency() for variable freq.
Decay m → Envelope decay rate: exp(-ρ(m) t) via MCU timer or analog RC on gate. Higher m = faster fade (short resonance "lifetime").
R_pruned & OPEN/CLOSED → Gate: If |R_pruned| > 0.5 → enable PWM output; else duty=0 (silent). Amplitude proportional to |R_pruned| (via PWM duty or op-amp gain).
Shear → FM: Add small freq deviation = shear_base(n) × 50–200 Hz (MCU adjusts PWM freq dynamically).
Pruning → If |R_gate| >13 → force short reset burst (e.g., 100 ms white noise or full-off).
Build steps: 
Wire MOSFET low-side driver (safe for piezo).
Upload code computing your full pipeline (R_pruned etc.) per loop.
Test: Dial (l,n,m) via buttons/encoder → hear/feel vibration change.
Measure: Phone spectrum app or oscilloscope on piezo leads.
This gives immediate "tunneling" feedback: OPEN states buzz/vibrate strongly with decaying tone, CLOSED = dead silence, n-shifts change pitch/harmonics, m-controls how long it rings.
2. RF Block Diagram (Microwave/UHF Cavity-Like Resonator – Next Level)
Goal: Closer to "black hole tube" physics — discrete cavity modes as energy bands, gain/attenuation as OPEN/CLOSED, Q-factor as decay bands.
Core Components (total ~$50–200 starter):
Microcontroller/SDR: Raspberry Pi + HackRF One / LimeSDR Mini / ADALM-Pluto (~$100–300) for control & monitoring
VCO/PLL: ADF4351 or Si5351 module (~$10–30) for tunable LO
Cavity/filter: DIY coaxial stub (copper pipe + SMA) or printed microstrip resonator (FR4 PCB) for UHF (433/915 MHz) or microwave (2.4/5.8 GHz)
Amplifier/attenuator: Mini-Circuits ERA or PGA series MMIC (~$5–20), PIN diode or varactor for gating
Coupler/detector: Directional coupler + diode detector for feedback
Power: 5 V USB + 12 V for amps
Block Diagram (Text Layout – Signal Flow)
[Control MCU / Pi] ──► Compute Portal Rules (l,n,m → R_pruned, state, shear FM)
                     │
                     ├─► Frequency Control ──► VCO/PLL (ADF4351/Si5351)
                     │     - Base freq = f_center(l) × (metallic(k)/n)   [e.g., 433 MHz base for l=0]
                     │     - + shear_mod × dev (50 kHz–1 MHz FM for drift)
                     │
                     ├─► Gate Control ──► PIN Diode / VCA / Switch
                     │     - OPEN (|R_pruned|>0.5): low attenuation / high gain
                     │     - CLOSED: high attenuation / off
                     │     - Gain ∝ |R_pruned| (via VCA voltage)
                     │
                     └─► Envelope/Decay ──► Analog or digital multiplier
                           - Decay time ∝ 1/ρ(m) (long ring for low m, fast ring-down for high m)
                           - Implemented as slow AGC loop or MCU-timed burst

[RF Path]
VCO output ──► Gate/Attenuator ──► Power Amp (MMIC) ──► Coupling Loop into Cavity
                                                        │
                                                        ├─► Cavity Resonator (coax stub / microstrip / reentrant)
                                                        │     - Tuned to ~metallic(k) multiples (discrete modes = layers/branches)
                                                        │     - Q-factor tuned by loading or varactor (maps to m-decay)
                                                        └─► Output Coupling Loop ──► Detector / SDR RX
                                                                              - Feedback to MCU for resonance lock / state viz
How It Maps Your Grammar
Layer l → Cavity mode/freq band (e.g., l=0 low UHF, l=4 microwave harmonics).
Branch n → Harmonic injection or mode selection (VCO × n).
Decay m → Loaded Q or ring-down time (higher m = more damping = faster decay).
OPEN/CLOSED → RF switch/gate (PIN diode on/off or VCA gain).
Shear → FM on VCO (cross-layer "drift" as frequency wobble).
Pruning → If chaos → force high attenuation burst or mode hop.
Build steps:
Start with Si5351 breakout + PIN diode switch for proof-of-concept (no cavity yet).
Add stub cavity (λ/4 coax shorted one end) tuned to ~your metallic ratios.
Monitor with RTL-SDR or phone SDR app → see peaks appear/disappear per state.
Ultrasonic first gives quick wins (vibration/audio feedback). RF next adds true cavity resonance feel.
